## Query 1
🔍 What this SQL is doing
This query creates a master view that calculates profitability at the individual product level for every order. It transforms raw sales data into "Net Margin" by accounting for discounts and unit costs, while also creating a specific "returned item flag" to help the business identify which specific products and brands are driving the highest return rates.

🎯 Skills Demonstrated
The script demonstrates data transformation by building calculated fields that handle complex business logic, such as zeroing out margins for returned items. It also showcases relational database expertise by successfully joining four disparate tables (orders, items, products, and customers) into a single, high-performance view optimized for BI tools like Tableau.

CREATE OR REPLACE VIEW [dbo.vw_product_performance] AS

SELECT
    o.order_id,
    o.customer_id,
    o.order_date,
    o.order_status,
    oi.product_id,
    oi.quantity,
    oi.unit_price AS item_price,
    oi.unit_cost AS item_cost,
    oi.item_discount,
    oi.item_returned,
    p.category,
    p.brand,
    p.avg_rating,
    p.product_name,

    ---- Order Item Level Calcs ----
    (oi.quantity * oi.unit_price) AS gross_order_item_revenue,
    (oi.quantity * oi.unit_cost)  AS gross_order_item_cost,
    (oi.quantity * oi.unit_price) - (oi.item_discount * oi.quantity) AS net_order_item_revenue,
   
    CASE
        WHEN oi.item_returned = 1 THEN 0
        ELSE (oi.quantity * oi.unit_price)
             - (oi.item_discount * oi.quantity)
             - (oi.quantity * oi.unit_cost)
    END AS net_order_item_margin,

    ---- Returned Flag ----
    CASE
        WHEN oi.item_returned = 1 THEN 1 
        ELSE 0
    END AS returned_item_flag

FROM orders o
INNER JOIN order_items oi
    ON o.order_id = oi.order_id
INNER JOIN products p
    ON p.product_id = oi.product_id
INNER JOIN customers c
    ON o.customer_id = c.customer_id;

## Query 2
🔍 What this SQL is doing
This query evaluates the "discount sensitivity" of every product in the catalog. It calculates the split between full-price and discounted sales for both volume and revenue, and then automatically flags products as "Discount Dependent" or "Full Price" based on how often they require a promotion to sell. This provides the data needed to stop "blanket discounting" on products that would have sold at full price anyway.

🎯 Skills Demonstrated
This script showcases advanced business logic and diagnostic modeling by creating custom categorisation tiers based on sales ratios. It demonstrates use of defensive programming (using NULLIF to prevent "divide by zero" errors) and precision rounding, ensuring that the resulting dataset is clean, statistically sound, and ready for senior-level strategic decision-making.

## Query 3
🔍 What this SQL is doing

The following query isolates every transaction over the last year to determine exactly how many products were sold for a loss versus a profit. It separates the total profit generated by successful sales from the total "leakage" caused by loss-making items, providing a clear picture of how much money is being lost to aggressive discounting.

🎯 Skills Demonstrated

The code demonstrates use of data modeling by using conditional logic to separate profitable sales from loss-making ones in a single, efficient step. By organizing the logic into a Common Table Expression (CTE), it shows an ability to write clean, modular code that turns complex raw data into clear financial insights.

WITH order_profitability AS (
    SELECT
        order_id,
        category,
        product_name,

        -- Quantity sold at a loss
        SUM(CASE
            WHEN net_order_item_revenue < gross_order_item_cost THEN quantity
            ELSE 0
        END) AS quantity_loss,

        -- Quantity sold at a profit
        SUM(CASE
            WHEN net_order_item_revenue >= gross_order_item_cost THEN quantity
            ELSE 0
        END) AS quantity_gain,

        -- Net loss from items sold at a loss
        SUM(CASE
            WHEN net_order_item_revenue < gross_order_item_cost 
            THEN net_order_item_revenue - gross_order_item_cost
            ELSE 0
        END) * -1.0 AS loss,

        -- Profit from profitable items
        SUM(CASE
            WHEN net_order_item_revenue >= gross_order_item_cost 
            THEN net_order_item_revenue - gross_order_item_cost
            ELSE 0
        END) AS gains

    FROM dbo.vw_category_performance
    WHERE order_date >= '2023-06-01'
      AND order_date <  '2024-06-01'
    GROUP BY
        order_id,
        category,
        product_name
)

## Query 4
🔍 What this SQL is doing
This query creates a high-level summary of every order to help the business understand why returns happen. It automatically categorizes orders as "Full," "Partial," or "No Return," identifies if a customer is shopping for the first time, and groups orders into "Low," "Average," or "High" value buckets based on their final spend.

🎯 Skills Demonstrated
This code showcases advanced analytical depth by using Window Functions (OVER PARTITION BY) to pinpoint specific customer milestones, like their very first order. It also demonstrates data architecture skills by joining multiple tables and using complex conditional logic to transform raw numbers into strategic categories like "Discount Level" and "Return Status."

CREATE VIEW vw_order_level_returns AS

SELECT 
    ---- Core Info ----
    o.order_id,
    CASE 
        WHEN SUM(item_returned) = 0 THEN 'No Returns'
        WHEN SUM(item_returned) = COUNT(o.order_id) THEN 'Fully Returned'
        ELSE 'Partially Returned'
    END AS order_return_status,

    ---- Customer Info ----
    o.customer_id,
    CASE
        WHEN order_date = MIN(order_date) OVER (PARTITION BY o.customer_id) THEN 1
        ELSE 0
    END AS customers_first_order,
    acquisition_channel,
    country,
    device_type,

    ---- Order Info ----
    channel,
    order_date,
    payment_method,
    CASE 
        WHEN SUM(item_discount * quantity) / SUM(unit_price * quantity) = 0 THEN 'None'
        WHEN SUM(item_discount * quantity) / SUM(unit_price * quantity) >= 0.2 THEN 'High'
        WHEN SUM(item_discount * quantity) / SUM(unit_price * quantity) >= 0.1 
             AND SUM(item_discount * quantity) / SUM(unit_price * quantity) < 0.2 THEN 'Average'
        WHEN SUM(item_discount * quantity) / SUM(unit_price * quantity) < 0.1 THEN 'Low'
    END AS discount_applied,

    CASE 
        WHEN (SUM(quantity * unit_price) - SUM(quantity * item_discount)) < 280 THEN 'Low'
        WHEN (SUM(quantity * unit_price) - SUM(quantity * item_discount)) >= 280 
             AND (SUM(quantity * unit_price) - SUM(quantity * item_discount)) < 840 THEN 'Average'
        WHEN (SUM(quantity * unit_price) - SUM(quantity * item_discount)) >= 840 THEN 'High'
    END AS order_value

FROM orders o
INNER JOIN order_items oi ON o.order_id = oi.order_id
INNER JOIN products p ON p.product_id = oi.product_id
INNER JOIN customers c ON c.customer_id = o.customer_id

GROUP BY 
    o.order_id,
    o.customer_id,
    order_date,
    acquisition_channel,
    country,
    device_type,
    channel,
    payment_method
